  "prompt": "Is it a fact that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, it is a fact that money laundering is against the law in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The purpose of money laundering is to make it appear as though the money comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, for example, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act** make it a criminal offense to knowingly engage in financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activity. Similar laws exist in other countries, often as part of broader anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks. International organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** also work to set global standards and promote enforcement of anti-money laundering laws.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include severe fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences, depending on the jurisdiction and the scale of the operation.",
